b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id385instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#booktitle'	b'Towards the Semantic Web \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x80\x9c Ontology-based Knowledge Management'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Personen/viewPersonOWL/id2139instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#name'	b'Sebastian Rudolph'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id595instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In recent years two main technologies for knowledge sharing and reuse have emerged: ontologies and problem solving methods (PSMs). Ontologies specify reusable conceptualizations which can be shared by multiple reasoning components communicating during a problem solving process. PSMs describe in a domain-independent way the generic reasoning steps and knowledge types needed to perform a task. Typically PSMs are specified in a task-specific fashion, using modelling frameworks which describe their control and inference structures as well as their knowledge requirements and competence. In this paper we discuss a novel approach to PSM specification, which is based on the use of formal ontologies. In particular our specifications abstract from control, data flow and other dynamic aspects of PSMs to focus on the logical theory associated with a PSM (method ontology). This approach concentrates on the competence and knowledge requirements of a PSM, rather than internal control details, thus enabling black-box-style reuse. In the paper we also look at the nature of PSM specifications and we show that these can be characterised in a task-independent style as generic search strategies. The resulting "modelling gap" between method-independent task specifications and task-independent method ontologies can be bridged by constructing the relevant adapter ontology, which reformulates the method ontology in task-specific terms. An important aspect of the ontology-centred approach described here is that, in contrast with other characterisations of task-independent PSMs, it does away with the simple, binary distinction between weak and strong methods. We argue that any method can be defined in either task-independent or task-dependent style and therefore such distinction is of limited utility in PSM reuse. The differences between PSMs which affect reuse concern the ontological commitments which they make with respect to domain knowledge and goal specifications.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id588instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Mit Fragen der methodischen Unterst\xc3\x83\xc2\xbctzung des Entwicklungsprozesses von Softwaresystemen besch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftigen sich verschiedene Teildisziplinen der Informatik. Speziell sind hier das Software Engineering, das Information Systems Engineering und das Knowledge Engineering zu nennen. W\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4hrend das Software Engineering insbesondere Beitr\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ge zur Beschreibung des Entwicklungsprozesses durch Vorgehensmodelle und zur Beschreibung (nicht-)funktionaler Aspekte von Softwaresystemen geliefert hat, besch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftigte man sich im Information Systems Engineering zun\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4chst prim\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4r mit der Modellierung statischer Aspekte von Informationssystemen durch semantische Datenmodelle. In den zur\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcckliegenden Jahren gewannen dynamische Aspekte jedoch immer mehr an Bedeutung. Im Knowledge Engineering wurden urspr\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcnglich haupts\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4chlich Fragen der methodischen Unters\xc3\x83\xc2\xbctzung der Wissenserhebung untersucht, in j\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcngster Zeit bekamen jedoch Methoden zur Wissensmodellierung und -wiederverwendung ein immer st\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4rkeres Gewicht.\r\nBei einer n\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4heren Betrachtung dieser Fachgebiete zeigt es sich, da\xc3\x83\xc5\xb8 einerseits eine Vielzahl gemeinsamer Fragestellungen und L\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6sungsans\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4tze existiert, andererseits aber auch sehr unterschiedliche Problemstellungen untersucht werden.\r\n[ . . . ]\r\nUm einen systematischen Vergleich der Methodiken zu erm\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6glichen, erarbeitete die Arbeitsgruppe einen Kriterienkatalog, mit dem charakteristische Eigenschaften einer Methodik erfa\xc3\x83\xc5\xb8t werden k\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6nnen. Dieser Kriterienkatalog wird nachfolgend verwendet, um jede der vier Methodiken detailliert zu charakterisieren. [aus der Einleitung]'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id15instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Metadata for the World Wide Web is important, but metadata for\r\nPeer-to-Peer (P2P) networks is absolutely\r\ncrucial. In this paper we discuss the open source project Edutella\r\nwhich builds upon metadata standards defined\r\nfor the WWW and aims to provide an RDF-based metadata infrastructure\r\nfor P2P applications, building on the\r\nrecently announced JXTA Framework. We describe the goals and main\r\nservices this infrastructure will provide\r\nand the architecture to connect Edutella Peers based on exchange of\r\nRDF metadata. As the query service is one\r\nof the core services of Edutella, upon which other services are\r\nbuilt, we specify in detail the Edutella Common\r\nData Model (ECDM) as basis for the Edutella query exchange language\r\nand format implementing distributed\r\nqueries over the Edutella network. Finally, we shortly discuss\r\nregistration and mediation services, and introduce\r\nthe prototype and application scenario for our current Edutella aware\r\npeers.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id537instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Access to XML-based documents currently relies on query languages that are closely tied to the document structures, i.e. when looking for information one has to be aware of this structure and cannot easily specify the information needs conceptually. Our approach uses ontologies to access sets of distributed XML documents on a conceptual level. We integrate conceptual modeling, inheritance, and inference mechanisms on the one hand with the popularity, simplicity, and flexibility of XML on the other hand. We present an approach that defines the relationship between a given ontology and a document type definition (DTD) for classes of XML documents. Thus, we are able to supplement syntactical access to XML documents by conceptual, i.e. real semantic access.'

The parametric cost\r\nestimation model ONTOCOM is a first attempt to cope with the\r\nlack of instruments for business measurements in the field of\r\nontology engineering. b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id404instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'One of the main strengths of an ontology-based system is the intensional description of the knowledge (information) about a domain, which is used in an inferencing process as a means of implying new domain knowledge. This inferencing process is very efficiently used for the explanation how an answer to a user\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s query was derived, increasing the trust of a user in the answers of the query. Moreover, such a derivation tree can be treated as an evidence of the relevance of an answer for the user\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s query. In this paper we present an approach which combines the derivation tree with the factual information in order to support the ranking of the results of an ontology-based query. Moreover, we discuss the possibilities to use such a ranking for clustering query\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s results. The approach has been implemented in the Ontobroker system, a main memory deductive database system.'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id411instance'	b'http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#Publication'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Forschungsgebiete/viewForschungsgebietOWL/id53instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#dealtWithIn'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Projekte/viewProjektOWL/id3instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1052instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Currently, the variety of expressive extensions and different semantics created for logic programs with negation is diverse and heterogeneous, and there is a lack of comprehensive comparative studies which map out the multitude of perspectives in a uniform way. Most recently, however, new methodologies have been proposed which allow one to derive uniform characterizations of different declarative semantics for logic programs with negation. In this paper, we study the relationship between two of these approaches, namely the level mapping characterizations due to [Hitzler and Wendt 2005], and the selector generated models due to [Schwarz 2004]. We will show that the latter can be captured by means of the former, thereby supporting the claim that level mappings provide a very flexible framework which is applicable to very diversely defined semantics.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id5instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#isAbout'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Forschungsgebiete/viewForschungsgebietOWL/id52instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1303instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Domains and metric spaces are two central tools for the study of denotational semantics in computer science, but are otherwise very different in many fundamental aspects. A construction that tries to establish links between both paradigms is the\r\nspace of formal balls, a continuous poset which can be defined for every metric space and that reflects many of its properties. On the other hand, in order to obtain a broader framework for applications and possible connections to domain theory, generalized ultrametric spaces (gums) have been introduced. In this paper, we employ the space of formal balls as a tool for studying these more general metrics by using\r\nconcepts and results from domain theory. It turns out that many properties of the\r\nmetric can be characterized via its formal-ball space. Furthermore, we can state new results on the topology of gums as well as two new fixed point theorems, which may be compared to the Prie\xc3\x83\xc5\xb8-Crampe and Ribenboim theorem, and the Banach fixed point theorem, respectively. Deeper insights into the nature of formal-ball spaces are gained by applying methods from category theory. Our results suggest that, while\r\nbeing a useful tool for the study of gums, the space of formal balls does not provide the hoped-for general connection to domain theory.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1116instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The vision of SEKT is to develop and exploit the knowledge\r\ntechnologies which underlie Next Generation Knowledge Management.\r\nWe envision knowledge workplaces where the boundaries between\r\ndocument management, content management, and knowledge management\r\nare broken down, and where knowledge management is an effortless\r\npart of day to day activities. SEKT is built around the synergy of\r\nthe complementary know-how of the key European centres of\r\nexcellence in Ontology and Metadata Technology, Knowledge\r\nDiscovery, and Human Language Technology. The execution of SEKT is\r\nbased on the integration of fundamental research, component\r\ndevelopment and integration driven by real world case studies in\r\nthe public and private sectors. SEKT will provide new insights on\r\nknowledge technologies.\r\n\r\nThe main objective of work package 7 is to provide a methodology\r\nfor the application of Semantic Knowledge Technologies into\r\nenterprises in a goal-driven and process-oriented way. The\r\ndeveloped SEKT methodology is applied and evaluated as part of the\r\ncase studies. In this report we collect the feedback from the case\r\nstudy partners. We present the enhancements of the methodology and\r\ninclude lessons learned and best practices.\r\n\r\nBased on this experiences we also designed two DILIGENT-based\r\ntools. EvA is meant for the distributed engineering of\r\nontologies, whereas the Semantic MediaWiki is best suited for the\r\npopulation of ontologies. We describe the design of these tools\r\nand some application scenarios.'

It presents the OWL API, a\r\n  high-level programmatic interface for accessing and manipulating OWL\r\n  ontologies. We discuss the underlying design issues and illustrate\r\n  possible solutions to technical issues occurring in systems that\r\n  intend to support the OWL standard. Although the context of our\r\n  solutions is that of a particular implementation, the issues\r\n  discussed are largely independent of this and should be of interest\r\n  to a wider community.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id411instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The goal of IBM\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s Autonomic Computing strategy is to deliver IT environments with improved self-management capabilities which cover the aspects of self-healing, self-protecting, self-optimizing, and self-configuring. Data correlation and inference technologies can be used as core components to build Autonomic Computing systems. They can be used to perform an automated, continuous analysis of enterprise-wide event data, based on user-defined, configurable rules, e.g. for detecting threats or system failures. Furthermore, they may trigger corrective actions for protecting or healing the system. \r\nIn this paper, we discuss the use of ontologies as a high-level, expressive conceptual modelling approach for describing the knowledge on which the processing of a   correlation engine is based upon. By introducing explicit models of state-based IT resources in the correlation technology approach, Autonomic Computing systems can be built which are able to deal with policy based goals on a higher abstraction level. We demonstrate some benefits of this approach by applying it to a particular IBM implementation, referred to as the \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc5\x93eAutomation\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xc2\x9d correlation engine.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1286instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"In the past, the focus of the computer industry has been to improve hardware performance and add more and more features to the software. As a result, more and more appliances surrounding us are equipped with embedded computational power and wireless communication. As such, they become ever more flexible and multifunctional, and almost indispensable in daily life. On the other hand, the resulting systems become increasingly complex and unreliable, posing new challenges to designer and user.\r\nOrganic Computing (OC) has the vision to address the challenges of complex distributed systems by making them more life-like (organic), i.e. endowing them with abilities such as self-organization, self-configuration, self-repair, or adaptation. The designer's task is simplified, because it is no longer necessary to exactly specify the low-level system behavior in all possible situations that might occur, but instead leaving the system with a certain degree of freedom which allows it to react in an intelligent way to new situations. Also, use of such systems is simplified, as they can be controlled by setting few high-level goals, rather than having to manipulate many low-level parameters with unclear influence.\r\nIn this paper, we give a general introduction to OC, and propose a generic observer-controller architecture as a framework for designing OC systems. Then, it is shown how to use this architecture at the example of a traffic light controller. The paper concludes with a summary and a discussion of future challenges."

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id569instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'm Folgenden werden unterschiedliche Vorgehensweisen zur Entwicklung wissensbasierter Systeme (WBS) aufgezeigt. In der Praxis noch weit verbreitet ist der Ansatz des Rapid Prototyping. Beim Rapid Prototyping wird informales Wissen unmittelbar in einer operationalen Wissensrepr\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4sentationsform oder einer Programmiersprache implementiert. Eine andere Vorgehensweise setzt sog. Role Limiting Methoden voraus. Role Limiting Methoden sind ausf\xc3\x83\xc2\xbchrbare Werkzeuge, die bereits alles Wissen zur L\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6sung von Problemen eines speziellen Typs enthalten. Sie m\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcssen nur noch um das bereichsspezifische Wissen angereichert werden. Bei modellbasierte Entwicklungsmethoden werden eine Reihe aufeinanderfolgender Modelle bis hin zum endg\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcltigen System entwickelt, deren Detaillierungs- und Formalisierungsgrad zunimmt. Der Beitrag skizziert alle drei Vorgehensweisen und zeigt deren Vor- und Nachteile und deren Einsatzgebiete auf.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id489instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Interoperability is one of the major design objectives when building applications for B2B and Semantic Web applications. In this paper, we present a methodology for engineering semantic knowledge such that these semantic structures are easier reusable when switching between several representa-tion languages. For this purpose, we re-consider the commonalities of representation languages and their usage in actual applica-tions. Out of this consideration we derive se-mantic patterns as a means to communicate knowledge at an epistemological level of rep-resentation and as a means for (partial) exe-cution by any particular implementation of any representation language. The underlying method we propose combines the advantages of formal specification methods (where fea-sible) with informal, natural language expla-nations such as used in software engineering for design patterns.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id805instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"Part of the theory of logic programming and nonmonotonic reasoning concerns\r\nthe study of fixed-point semantics for these paradigms. Several different\r\nsemantics have been proposed during the last two decades, and some have been\r\nmore successful and acknowledged than others. The rationales behind those\r\nvarious semantics have been manifold, depending on one's point of view,\r\nwhich may be that of a programmer or inspired by commonsense reasoning, and\r\nconsequently the constructions which lead to these semantics are technically\r\nvery diverse, and the exact relationships between them have not yet been fully understood. In this paper, we present a conceptually new method, based\r\non level mappings, which allows to provide uniform characterizations of\r\ndifferent semantics for logic programs. We will display our approach by\r\ngiving new and uniform characterizations of some of the major semantics,\r\nmore particular of the least model semantics for definite programs, of the\r\nFitting semantics, and of the well-founded semantics. A novel\r\ncharacterization of the weakly perfect model semantics will also be\r\nprovided."

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id664instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Not only knowledge acquisition, but also the principled transition from knowledge acquisition to implementation is an important question in knowledge engineering. This paper focuses on this transition and characterises the design phase of the MIKE approach to model-based incremental development of knowledge-based systems. The role of non-functional requirements in the development process is discussed and it is argued that for reasons of transparency, the description of the design should not just contain the description of the artefact, but should additionally include a record of the design decisions and their motivation, i.e. their relationship to the requirements posed. DesignKARL is outlined as the formalism for describing the artefact as well as design decisions and their rationale in MIKE.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1342instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In this paper we describe an infrastructure for query answering over\r\ndistributed ontologies on the Semantic Web. This infrastructure\r\naddresses (i) the coordination of multiple nodes using metadata\r\nabout the provided resources managed in a decentralized registry and\r\n(ii) the mediation between heterogeneous ontologies via an\r\nexpressive mapping formalism along with corresponding reasoning\r\nalgorithms for query answering. Our approach is based on a virtual\r\nintegration that exhibits a semantics as if all ontologies were\r\nintegrated locally. Practically, the distributed ontologies still\r\nreside on the remote peers, and only the parts relevant for\r\nanswering the query need to be retrieved to the local node.\r\nExperimental evaluations with the implementation in KAONp2p show\r\nthat the approach is very promising, as the performance of query\r\nanswering is essentially dominated by the size of the data, and only\r\nslightly affected by the degree of distribution and heterogeneity.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id403instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In this paper, we present an agent-based approach for the improvement of searching in an ontology-based knowledge management system. The system implements a library scenario in which users query the repository for knowledge resources. Consequently, the so-called Librarian Agent plays the role of the human librarian in the traditional library \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x80\x9c it uses all possible information, about the domain vocabulary, the behaviour of previous users and the capacity of the knowledge repository, in order to help users find the resources they are interested in. We partially implemented the approach in the Web Portal of our Institute and some initial evaluation results are shown.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1066instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Both OWL-DL and function-free Horn rules are decidable fragments of first-order logic with interesting, yet orthogonal expressive power. A combination of OWL-DL and rules is desirable for the Semantic Web; however, it might easily lead to the undecidability of interesting reasoning problems. Here, we present a decidable such combination where rules are required to be DL-safe: each variable in the rule is required to occur in a non-DL-atom in the rule body. We discuss the expressive power of such a combination and present an algorithm for query answering in the related logic SHIQ extended with DL-safe rules, based on a reduction to disjunctive programs.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id444instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Identifying and presenting useful information for a given context is an important challenge for research and development of Web technologies.Providing access to information for humans and machines is one of the main motivations for the Semantic Web. Our contribution to the 2003 Semantic Web Grand Challenge realizes semantic-based search and access facilities to information represented by semantic portals. Such portals typically provide knowledge about a specific domain and rely on ontologies to structure and exchange this knowledge. Computer science exploits ontologies to enhance knowledge sharing and reuse. First, ontologies provide a common, shared understanding of knowledge in an interest domain. Second, they capture and formalize knowledge by connecting human understanding of symbols with their machine processability. As such, ontologies play a key role for realizing the Semantic Web.\r\nOur contribution extends and implements the basic conceptual framework SEAL (SEmantic portAL) with the aim of using semantic technologies in real-world scenarios through a reliable, scalable infrastructure. We also show how multiple semantic portals can interact with one another to exchange knowledge, thus fostering reuse. The building blocks of our extension include knowledge integration, processing, representation, organization, and access. Our approach has these benefits: (i) Significant reduction of content maintenance overhead, (ii) knowledge accessibility for both human and machine agents, atop existing information sources, and (iii) suitability for productive environments.'

However, while the\r\nintegration with propositional paradigms has resulted\r\nin applicable systems, the case of first-order\r\nknowledge representation has so far hardly proceeded\r\nbeyond theoretical studies which prove the\r\nexistence of connectionist systems for approximating\r\nfirst-order logic programs up to any chosen precision.\r\nAdvances were hindered severely by the\r\nlack of concrete algorithms for obtaining the approximating\r\nnetworks which were known to exist:\r\nthe corresponding proofs are not constructive\r\nin that they do not yield concrete methods for\r\nbuilding the systems. b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1299instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Horn-SHIQ has been identified as a fragment of the description logic SHIQ for which inferencing is in PTime with respect to the size of the ABox. This enables reasoning with larger ABoxes in situations where the TBox is static, and represents one approach towards tractable description logic reasoning. \r\n\r\n\r\nIn this paper, we show that reasoning in Horn-SHIQ, in spite of its low data-complexity, is ExpTime-hard with respect to the overall size of the knowledge base. While this result is not unexpected, the proof is not a mere modification of existing reductions since it has to account for the restrictions of Hornness. We establish the result for Horn-FLE, showing that Hornness does not simplify TBox reasoning even for very restricted description logics. Moreover, we derive a context-free grammar that defines Horn-SHIQ in a simpler and more intuitive way than existing characterisations.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Personen/viewPersonOWL/id57instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#publication'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id659instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id636instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Learning from examples is a field of research in machine learning where class descriptions, like decision trees or implications (production rules or horn clauses) are produced using positive and negative examples as information. To solve this task many different heuristic search strategies have been developed, so far. The search by specialization is the most widely used search strategy, whereas other approaches use a search by generalization only. JoJo is an algorithm that combines both search directions into one search procedure. According to the estimated quality of the currently regarded rule either a generalization or specialization step is carried out by deleting or adding one premise to the conjunction part of the rule. But, to create an even more flexible (and faster) algorithm, it should be possible to delete or add more than just one premise at a time. Relaxing this restriction of JoJo led to the new highly flexible algorithm Frog that additionally uses a third search direction.'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id615instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Uncertainty, incompleteness and vagueness are typical features of common-sense as well as expert knowledge. Reasoning based on such knowledge demands strategies to combine divergent information. All the more this is true in the context of integrating knowledge bases. This paper addresses knowledge representation, reasoning, and conflict management with many-valued logics. We show by some examples how information can be expressed in many-valued Horn clauses, how fitting truth value spaces can be found -in this context we also consider bilattices- and how conflict solving strategies can be involved. We do not focus on technical details but try to open up prospects of applications.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id70instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In this paper, we present a novel approach for the management of the ontology-based knowledge management system. The approach is mainly based on the analysis of the users\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2 behaviour in two phases of a knowledge management cycle: (i) in providing knowledge by analysing the quality of annotations and (ii) in searching for knowledge by analysing users\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2 queries and the responses from the knowledge repository. This analysis results in the recommendations for changes in the underlying ontology, the annotations and/or the knowledge repository in order to make the whole system more efficient. We present two short case studies.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id510instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Skill management systems serve as technical platforms for mostly, though not exclusively, corporate-internal market places for skills and know-how. The systems are typically built on top of a database that contains profiles of employees and applicants. Thus, the skills may be retrieved through database queries. However, these approaches incur two major problems, viz. the finding of approximate matches and the maintenance of skill data. In this paper we describe two systems that leverage corporate skill knowledge by offering advanced means for both. We present ProPer that uses means from decision theory to allow for compensate skill matching. Then, we describe OntoProPer that combines these methods with intelligent means for inferencing of skill data. For the latter an ontology provides background knowledge, i.e. conceptual structures and rules, which supplement the skill database with ground and inferred facts from secondary information, such as project documents. These supplement facts re-duce maintenance efforts since much secondary information is gathered in the organizational memory through common working tasks. Keywords: skill management, human resource management, ontologies, intranet application.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id604instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The paper presents an approach for using a bidirectional search strategy for inductively learning clauses in a restricted first-order language. The learning target is to find a set of goal clauses that describe the true ground facts of a given target predicate. In our example setting we further assume that the background knowledge is also given in the form of true (and false) ground facts of each background predicate. By fixing the number of variables allowed in the derived clauses we show that no explicit negative goal facts are needed in the case of the closed-world assumption since the rules are evaluated from the premise to the head rather than binding the variables of the goal literal first. As a consequence we get an efficient ILP algorithm that tries to minimize the tuples of variable substitutions stored at each step of our covering approach.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id526instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The problem of the relevance and the usefulness of extracted association rules is of primary importance because, in the majority of cases, real-life databases lead to several thousands association rules with high confidence and among which are many redundancies. Using the closure of the Galois connection, we define two new bases for association rules which union is a generating set for all valid association rules with support and confidence. These bases are characterized using frequent closed itemsets and their generators; they consist of the non-redundant exact and approximate association rules having minimal antecedents and maximal consequents, i.e. the most relevant association rules. Algorithms for extracting these bases are presented and results of experiments carried out on real-life databases show that the proposed bases are useful, and that their generation is not time consuming.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1181instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Knowledge representation and semantic annotation of multimedia documents typically have been pursued in two different directions. Previous approaches have focused either on low-level descriptors, such as dominant colour, or on the semantic content dimension and corresponding manual annotations, such as person or vehicle. Here, a knowledge infrastructure and an experimentation platform for semantic annotation to bridge the two directions are presented. Ontologies are being extended and enriched to include low-level audiovisual features and descriptors. Additionally, a tool that allows for linking low-level MPEG-7 visual descriptions to ontologies and annotations is presented. Thus, ontologies that include prototypical instances of high-level domain concepts together with a formal specification of the corresponding visual descriptors are constructed. This infrastructure is exploited by a knowledge-assisted analysis framework that may handle problems such as segmentation, tracking, feature extraction and matching in order to classify scenes, identify and label objects and thus automatically create the associated semantic metadata.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id584instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#author'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Personen/viewPersonOWL/id41instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id599instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Building knowledge-based systems from reusable elements is a key factor in their economic development. However, one has to ensure that the assumptions and functionality of the reused building block fit to each other and the specific circumstances of the actual problem and knowledge. We use the Karlsruhe Interactive Verifier (KIV) for this purpose. We show how the verification of conceptual and formal specifications of knowledge-based systems can be done with it. KIV was originally developed for the verification of procedural programs but it fits well for verifying knowledge-based systems. Its specification language is based on algebraic specification means for the functional specification of components and dynamic logic for the algorithmic specification. It provides an interactive theorem prover integrated into a sophisticated tool environment supporting aspects like the automatic generation of proof obligations, generation of counter examples, proof management, proof reuse etc. Such a support is essential in making verification of complex specifications feasible. We provide some examples on how to specify and verify tasks, problem-solving methods, and their relationships. \r\nAn earlier version was appeared as: Specifying and Verifying Knowledge-Based Systems with KIV. In Proceedings of the European Symposium on the Validation and Verification of Knowledge Based Systems EUROVAV-97, Leuven Belgium, June 26-28, 1997.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id143instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Description logic is expected to play a key role in ontology\r\nmodeling for the Semantic Web. However, logic programming paradigm\r\nhas been researched extensively in the past and has a large user\r\ncommunity, so interoperability between these two formalisms is a\r\ndesirable and an important issue. In this paper we extend our\r\nexisting work on translation of description logics ontologies to\r\nlogic programs. In particular we handle additional expressive\r\nprimitives, such as existentials, equality, functional properties\r\nand nominals. We show how to apply our approach for answering\r\nqueries over DL ontologies. Finally, we empirically analyse the\r\nbenefits of our approach in practise by comparing the performance\r\nof query answering using state-of-the-art description logics\r\nsystems and using our translation in conjunction with available\r\nlogic programming systems.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1278instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Das erfolgreiche Management und damit das Planen, Steuern und Kontrollieren von unternehmensinternen und -\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcbergreifenden Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozessen stellt einen zentralen Erfolgsfaktor f\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcr Unternehmen dar. Ein Defizit bisheriger Modellierungssprachen, Methoden und Werkzeuge zum kennzahlenbasierten Management von Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozessen besteht darin, dass Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozesse und Kennzahlen in getrennten Schemata modelliert werden. Kausale Zusammenh\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4nge zwischen Kennzahlen und Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozessen werden bisher durch Plausibilit\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4tspr\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcfungen ermittelt und k\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6nnen weder validiert noch verifiziert werden. \r\nIm Rahmen dieser Arbeit wird eine Vorgehensweise auf Basis von so genannten Performance-Netzen vorgestellt, die hierzu einen phasen\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcbergreifenden Ansatz zum kennzahlenbasierten Management von Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozessen anbietet. Performance-Netze sind eine neue Variante h\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6herer Petri-Netze und erlauben die integrierte Darstellung von Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozessen, der relevanten Kennzahlen, der daf\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcr definierten Zielwerte und der entsprechenden Korrekturprozesse. Anhand von Beispielen wird gezeigt, wie Performance-Netze die schrittweise Modellierung von semi-formalen, anwendungsnahen einfachen Petri-Netzen zu formalen, maschinell ausf\xc3\x83\xc2\xbchrbaren kennzahlenbasierten h\xc3\x83\xc2\xb6heren Petri-Netzen unterst\xc3\x83\xc2\xbctzen. Die Architektur und prototypische Realisierung eines Modellierungs-, Simulations- und Kontrollwerkzeugs f\xc3\x83\xc2\xbcr Performance-Netze wird pr\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4sentiert. Am Beispiel einer Fallstudie wird die grunds\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4tzliche Praktikabilit\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4t des kennzahlenbasierten Managements von Gesch\xc3\x83\xc2\xa4ftsprozessen mit Performance-Netzen und deren Implementierung gezeigt und evaluiert.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1140instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Today, most computer users work with traditional hierarchical file systems\r\nfor organizing large amounts of personal files. Recently, tagging has grown popular as an alternative means of organizing information resources. We argue that tagging is a\r\npowerful paradigm for efficient information access which overcomes many deficiencies of hierarchical file systems, especially in the context of the organization of large quantities of personal files. In this paper we present TagFS, a filesystem with tagging support\r\nwhich aims at a seamless integration of the tagging paradigm with local applications.\r\nWhile retaining the notions of directories and files and providing all standard filesystem operations, the semantics of these primitives are changed to modifications of the tag annotations.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id54instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Quality information systems (QIS) are providing all the quality-relevant information during the whole life cycle of a product to all the people involved. With regard to e-learning applications this means that a QIS should provide quality-relevant information to the authors of e-learning materials as well as to the instructors and the learners using them. In this work it is described how such a QIS can be implemented in the context of e-learning applications. In this connection a prototypic system design and strategies for the integration of a QIS into the information system infrastructure of e-learning providers are presented.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id400instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In this paper we presented a framework for the query refinement which is driven by the user\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s information needs. Based on the analyses of the real IR case studies we gathered the requirements and modeled the query refinement process as the process of changing query ambiguity according to a user \xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xcb\x9cs need. We define several semantic and structural ambiguities, implied by the used vocabulary and information repository, respectively. As our evaluation study shows, the usability of the approach overcomes the traditional information retrieval problems and enables the realisation of an e-shop-assistant in the e-commerce applications.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id415instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'We present the Web Service Description Framework (WSDF), which provides both a representation mechanism and a runtime system architecture for semantically enriched Web Services. We analyze existing languages such as BPEL4WS and OWL-S before addressing their deficiencies in our proposal. Our approach allows a client to invoke a service based solely on a shared ontology, i.e. without prior knowledge on the API, providing an important building block towards a global, flexible information infrastructure. Another main point is that WSDF can be applied to clients and services written in a conventional object oriented programming language. This is achieved by lifting datastructures to an ontology level in which rich logical statements about services can be formalized. We also present a detailed system architecture that covers planning, invocation, and the automatic processing of the service results, which is accomplished using the observer design pattern and by asserting the result in the respective model. Furthermore, the required annotations can be specified conveniently by placing comments in the source code.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id947instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'e-Skills certification plays a crucial role implementing and promoting high standards among ICT professionals/ practitioners and ICT end users. CEPIS studied on behalf of Cedefop the situation of e-Skills Certification in Europe. The study identified voluntary approaches offered by widely applied e-skills certifications. The operational objective for this study has been the evaluation of issues of e-skills certification at the International and European level by analysing attitudes of stakeholders towards current and future European level activities and highlighting potential solutions and recommendations to perceived problems. Based on the achieved results and outcome of the conducted study, the authors propose and illustrate a possible path towards internationally agreed certifications and recognised qualifications throughout Europe.'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id493instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'One of the core challenges for the Semantic Web is the aspect of decentralization. Local structures can be modeled by ontologies. How- ever, in order to support global communication and knowledge exchange, mechanisms have to be developed for integrating the local systems. We adopt the database approach of autonomous federated database systems and consider an architecture for federated ontologies for the Semantic Web as starting point of our work. We identify the need for merging specific ontologies for developing feder- ated, but still autonomous web systems. We present the method FCA{ Merge for merging ontologies following a bottom-up approach which offers a structural description of the merging process. The method is guided by application-specific instances of the given source ontologies that are to be merged. We apply techniques from natural language pro- cessing and formal concept analysis to derive a lattice of concepts as a structural result of FCA{Merge. The generated result is then explored and transformed into the merged ontology with human interaction.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1330instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The paper reports on the activities and results of a survey of certification schemes of ICT professionals across Europe towards harmonisation. The survey was undertaken by a consortium of nine organisations in Europe. The survey covers 36 professional informatics societies in 32 European countries, representing more than 400.000 ICT professionals in Europe. The European countries directly involved and represented in the consortium are the leading national professional informatics societies in Estonia, Germany, Hungary, Italy and United Kingdom. The paper describes the survey approach developed, survey methodology applied and overviews and discusses preliminary results of the survey activity.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id786instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Formal concept analysis has grown from a new branch of the mathematical\r\nfield of lattice theory to a widely recognized tool in Computer Science\r\nand elsewhere. In order to fully benefit from this theory, we believe that it\r\ncan be enriched with notions such as approximation by computation or representability. The latter are commonly studied in denotational semantics and domain theory and captured most prominently by the notion of algebraicity, e.g. of lattices. In this paper, we explore the notion of algebraicity in formal concept analysis from a category-theoretical perspective. To this end, we build on the the notion of approximable concept with a suitable category and show that the latter is equivalent to the category of algebraic lattices. At the same time, the paper provides a relatively comprehensive account of the representation theory of algebraic lattices in the framework of Stone duality, relating well-known structures such as Scott information systems with further formalisms from logic, topology, domains and lattice theory.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id606instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'New KARL (Knowledge Acquisition and Representation Language) allows to specify all parts of a problem-solving method (PSM). It is a formal language with a well-defined semantics and thus allows to represent PSMs precisely and unambiguously yet abstracting from implementation detail. In this paper it is shown how the language KARL has been modified and extended to New KARL to better meet the needs for the representation of PSMs. Based on a conceptual structure of PSMs new language primitives are introduced for KARL to specify such a conceptual structure and to support the configuration of methods. An important goal for this extension was to preserve three important properties of KARL: to be (i) a conceptual, (ii) a formal, and (iii) an executable language.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1243instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"Ontologies have been widely accepted as the primary method of\r\nrepresenting knowledge in the Semantic Web. Knowledge Elicitation (KE)\r\nis usually one of the first steps in building ontologies. A number\r\nof ontology editors such as Protege have been developed to\r\nassist users in building ontologies efficiently. However,\r\ntraditional KE techniques, such as card sorting\r\nand laddering, are not yet supported, but performed manually and\r\noutside of such tools.  In this paper we present a methodology and\r\na corresponding plug-in for Protege that allows\r\ngraphical ellicitation knowledge from documents using card sorting\r\nand laddering approaches. Our aim is to seamlessly integrate the\r\nKE techniques into the ontology building\r\nprocess to make ontology building more efficient and less\r\nerror-prone. As a side-effect the persistent storage of card\r\nsorting and laddering results allows for later traceability of ontology development.\r\nKE largely depends on user interaction with the\r\nplug-in, therefore we employed user-centred design principles to\r\ncapture requirements. After implementation, the plug-in was\r\nevaluated thoroughly against the requirements. The evaluation\r\nshows that this KE plug-in meets many of the\r\nuser's expectations and indeed saves them considerable time when\r\nbuilding ontologies."

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id125instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'An ontology over a period of time needs to be modified to reflect changes in the real world, changes in the user\xc3\xa2\xe2\x82\xac\xe2\x84\xa2s requirements, drawbacks in the initial design, to incorporate additional functionality or to allow for incremental improvement. Although changes are inevitable during the development and deployment of an ontology, most of the current ontology editors unfortunately do not provide enough support for efficient copying with changes. Since changes are the force that drives the evolution process, in this paper we discuss the requirements for the ontology editors in order to support ontology evolution.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1200instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#isAbout'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Forschungsgebiete/viewForschungsgebietOWL/id70instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id456instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"Standards in e-learning have been developed to support authoring, assembly, and execution of learning objects. Due to the fact that until now e learning is mainly applied in academic teaching, pricing of learning objects still plays a minor role in current research. So far, standards for learning objects lack concepts for the integration of prices. In this paper, we present an approach to support pricing of e-learning objects on different abstraction levels. The approach is based on combining price models and learning objects by extending the learning objects' XML metadata on the one hand and on the representation of processes as exchanges and manipulations of XML documents on the other hand. Consideration of price models in a workflow-based learning-object management system thus allows for explicitly modeling processes for pricing such as price negotiations between learners and learning object providers or mediators. Moreover, pricing processes can be integrated into learning, teaching, and administration processes and thereby enhance the cooperation of all participating actors."

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id840instance'	b'http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#Publication'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id418instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Due to the fast growth of internet based electronic business activities, languages for modeling as well as methods for analyzing and executing distributed business processes are becoming more and more important. Efficient inter-organizational business processes in the field of e-commerce require the integration of electronic document interchange and inter-organizational process management. We propose to support inter-organizational business processes by so-called XML nets, a new variant of high-level Petri nets. XML nets are a formal, graphical modeling language that allows to model both the flow of XML documents and the control flow of the underlying business process. XML nets are based on GXSL, a novel graphical XML schema definition language, and its related graphical XML document manipulation language XManiLa. They can be directly executed by a respective workflow engine. Advantage of the formal foundation of XML nets can be taken, e.g., when analyzing a (global) inter-organizational workflow model. XML nets support the identification of relevant process fragments and their allocation to the appropriate organizational units. Thus XML nets help to derive an improved, process-oriented organizational structure.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1344instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Semantic Wikis allow users to semantically annotate their\r\nWiki content. The particular annotations can differ in expressive power,\r\nsimplicity, and meaning. We present an elaborate conceptual model for\r\nsemantic annotations, introduce a unique and rich Wiki syntax for these\r\nannotations, and discuss how to best formally represent the augmented\r\nWiki content. We improve existing navigation techniques to automatically\r\nconstruct faceted browsing for semistructured data. By utilising\r\nthe Wiki annotations we provide greatly enhanced information retrieval.\r\nFurther we report on our ongoing development of these techniques in our\r\nprototype SemperWiki.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id619instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The paper presents an approach for machine learning in a restricted first-order language with finite minimal Herbrand models by means of a search through a propositional representation space. The learning target is to find a set of goal clauses which can be used to define a target predicate. That is, we deal with single-predicate learning. For the search process we use the learning algorithm JoJo/Frog which provides a flexible search strategy. The transition from the first-order representation to the representation in propositional logic is achieved by ground substitutions which transform clauses into ground clauses. Taking a closer look at this transition makes clear that the sufficiency condition which is used by algorithms like FOIL and LINUS as a criterion for judging the achieved learning results does not correspond to the completeness condition in the propositional case. Therefore, we use an extended completeness condition which captures all information given by the example knowledge. As a consequence we get a new definition of positive and negative examples. Instead of ground facts we regard ground substitutions as examples.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id568instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'This paper gives an overview about the development of the field of Knowledge Engineering over the last 15 years. We discuss the paradigm shift from a transfer view to a modeling view and describe two approaches which considerably shaped research in Knowledge Engineering: Role-limiting Methods and Generic Tasks. To illustrate various concepts and methods which evolved in the last years we describe three modeling frameworks: CommonKADS, MIKE, and PROT\xc3\x83\xe2\x80\xb0G\xc3\x83\xe2\x80\xb0-II. This description is supplemented by discussing some important methodological developments in more detail: specification languages for knowledge-based systems, problem-solving methods, and ontologies. We conclude with outlining the relationship of Knowledge Engineering to Software Engineering, Information Integration and Knowledge Management.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id688instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The intention of the workshop is to bring together researchers from the two research areas Semantic Web and Knowledge Discovery. According to T. Berners-Lee the Semantic Web is "an extension of the current web in which information is given well-defined meaning, better enabling computers and people to work in cooperation". Current standardization efforts include e.g. the W3C recommendation for the Web Ontology Language (OWL). Knowledge Discovery is defined by U.M. Fayyad as "the nontrivial process of identifying valid, previously unknown, potentially useful patterns in data". \r\nWe foresee two ways of combining these areas. On the one hand, mining for the semantic web includes the application of knowledge discovery methods and techniques to support the setting up of the semantic web itself. Prominent examples are here ontology learning and population of ontologies (instance learning). On the other hand, mining from the semantic web emphasizes the usage of semantic web technologies for mining purposes such as e.g. the usage of taxonomies in recommender systems, applying association rules with generalizations or clustering with background knowledge in form of ontologies.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1050instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The web ontology language OWL is still a very young language.\r\nExperience with the language will build an increasing pool of\r\nontology design patterns and best practises.\r\nIn this paper we introduce macros for OWL ontologies. Macros are able to\r\nformally specify and capture design patterns for the knowledge engineering\r\ntask with OWL ontologies. Thus the user is enabled to conveniently\r\nreuse them. Macros lead to an enhanced maintainability of the ontology,\r\nto a higher level of abstraction in the specification (and thus closer to\r\nthe human conceptualization), to a faster and less error-prone creation\r\nof the ontology (and thus to lower costs) and to automation of several\r\ntedious tasks in the ontology life cycle.\r\nWe present example macros, discuss further applications, advantages and\r\nproblems of macros, and discuss the development of an implementation\r\nto enable the usage of macros.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1184instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Ontologies are defined as the formal specification of a shared conceptualisation of a domain of interest. Unlike most other ontology engineering methodologies, the DILIGENT methodology aims specifically at the collaborative and distributed building of ontologies, providing a rich argumentation framework in order to quickly proceed with building the ontology and track all relevant discussions about the conceptualisation.\r\n\r\nBased upon first experience with the DILIGENT methodology, we designed a tool to support engineers and domain experts to follow the DILIGENT processes. In this paper we present the requirements, personas and scenarios our work is based upon, derived from our experience with ontology building, and the resulting design and state of the ongoing implementation, in order to get timely feedback for the further development of an DILIGENT based collaborative ontology engineering environment.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1059instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Logic programming has always been a major ontology\r\nmodeling paradigm, and is frequently being used in large\r\nresearch projects and industrial applications, e.g., by means\r\nof the F-Logic reasoning engine OntoBroker or the TRIPLE\r\nquery, inference, and transformation language and system.\r\nAt the same time, the Web Ontology Language OWL has\r\nbeen recommended by the W3C for modeling ontologies for\r\nthe web. Naturally, it is desirable to investigate the interoperability\r\nbetween both paradigms. In this paper, we do so\r\nby studying an expressive fragement of OWL DL for which\r\nreasoning can be reduced to the evaluation of Horn logic\r\nprograms. Building on the KAON2 algorithms for transforming\r\nOWL DL into disjunctive Datalog, we give a detailed\r\naccount of how and to what extent OWL DL can be\r\nemployed in standard logic programming systems. En route,\r\nwe derive a novel, simplified characterization of the supported\r\nfragment of OWL DL.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1086instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"For many real-world optimization problems, the robustness of a solution is of great importance in addition to the solution's quality. By robustness, we mean that small deviations from the original design, e.g., due to manufacturing tolerances, should be tolerated without a severe loss of quality. One way to achieve that goal is to evaluate each solution under a number of different scenarios, and use the average solution quality as fitness. However, this approach is often impractical, because the cost for evaluating each individual several times is unacceptable. In this paper, we present a new and efficient approach to estimating a solution's expected quality and variance. Basically, we propose to construct local approximate models of the fitness function, and then use these approximate models to estimate expected fitness and variance. Based on a variety of test function, we demonstrate empirically that our approach significantly outperforms the implicit averaging approach as well as the explicit averaging approaches using existing estimation techniques reported in the literature."

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Forschungsgruppen/viewForschungsgruppeOWL/id3instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#publishes'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id556instance'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id629instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"The paper attempts a step in the direction of competence theories of reusable problem-solving methods (psm's). In fact, we examine a variant of the psm propose-and-revise. The variant was developed as a solution to the current Sisyphus task (VT-task). We decompose the entire method into its individual subtasks and examine each subtask for its underlying assumptions concerning the available domain knowledge. By doing this, we determine assumptions and limitations of the entire method. In addition, we examine how different control flows between these subtasks can influence the efficiency and effectiveness of the method. Again, we show how these differences are related to the assumptions of the method. Making these assumptions explicit defines interesting goals for validation and verification efforts. First, we show that under some circumstances two psm's behave equally well or that one is more suitable than another. Second, we have to prove for a given domain knowledge whether it fulfils the assumptions of a selected problem-solving method. We believe that such studies are necessary to allow the reuse of psm's and, conversely, that the reuse of psm's justifies the effort of such activities."

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Personen/viewPersonOWL/id29instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#worksAtProject'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Projekte/viewProjektOWL/id63instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id611instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'The paper introduces a formal approach for the specification and verification of knowledge-based systems. We identify different elements of such a specification: a task definition, a problem-solving method, a domain model, an adapter, and assumptions that relate these elements. We present abstract data types and a variant of dynamic logic as formal means to specify these different elements. Based on our framework we can distinguish several verification tasks. In the paper, we discuss the application of the Karlsruhe Interactive Verifier (KIV) for this purpose. KIV was originally developed for the verification of procedural programs but it fits well for our approach. We illustrate the verification process with KIV and show how KIV can be used as an exploration tool that helps to detect assumptions necessary to close the gap between the task definition and the competence of a problem-solving method.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id364instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In this paper we present an approach to model ontology evolution as reconfiguration-design problem solving. The problem is reduced to a graph search where the nodes are evolving ontologies and the edges represent the changes that transform the source node into the target node. The search is guided by the constraints provided partially by a user and partially by a set of rules defining ontology consistency. In this way we allow a user to specify an arbitrary request declaratively and ensure its resolving. The approach is implemented in the KAON framework and the evaluation study shows its benefits.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id579instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'This paper describes research that is performed in the course of a project where a methodology for providing user support for KDD processes plays a central role. Although methodologically we aim at supporting the whole process of applying inductive learning techniques, the current paper focusses on a part of this process. The main issue in this paper is the support of data preprocessing for KDD. One of our experiences is that preprocessing of data possibly is the most time consuming part of Data Mining applications, and is almost always included in an application of machine learning. We give some insights in the metadata we calculate from a dataset as part of the method for user support and focus on how metadata can be used to guide preprocessing definition in combination with top down task decomposition. DCT (Data Characterisation Tool) is implemented in a software environment (Clementine). Some examples are given that resulted from running the UGM/DCT (User Guidance Module combined with DCT) on the data.\r\nFinally we will provide some examples based on UCI datasets and consider the improvements we made w.r.t. other approaches as well as what we gained using this extension to our User Guidance Module (UGM) for user support.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1266instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Integrating relational databases is recently acknowledged as an important vision of the Semantic Web research, however there is not many applications that are well-implemented and in large-scale real use. This paper introduces an in-use application deployed at China Academy of Traditional Chinese Medicine (CATCM). In this application, over 70 heterogeneous relational databases are semantically interconnected by an shared ontology with over 70 classes and 800 properties, providing semantic query and web search services to the Chinese Traditional Medicine (TCM) community like one huge database. A visualized mapping tool is developed to facilitate domain experts in defining semantic mappings from heterogeneous relational schemas to the shared ontology. The query interface is dynamically generated based on class definitions, and able to rewrite SPARQL queries to a set of SQL queries. An intuitive search interface enables user to get more accurate and reliable search results based on a concepts ranking mechanism. Feedbacks and evaluation results from CATCM indicate that they are mostly satisfied with this novel Semantic Web technologies enabled application.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id586instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"The rapid-prototyping approach of the early 1980's failed to deliver high-quality knowledge-based systems. As a reaction, in the early 90's, there has been a large activity in the knowledge engineering community to define methodologies for principled knowledge-based system development. These methodologies (e.g., CommonKADS, MIKE, VITAL, TASK) succeeded in organising the development process as a set of intermediate models of the functionality of the system to be built, to end in the final implementation. Feedback from industries that use these methodologies in practice reveals, however, that building a high-quality implemented system remains a difficult and error-prone process. The main reason for this is that, although the structure of the development process is rather well understood, the transition process is less clear. In this paper, we outline an approach for assuring the transition of a conceptual model into a final implementation which satisfies particular quality criteria. The approach is based on identifying adequate transition paths and activities on models in order to achieve particular quality criteria. An essential part of the approach is formed by methodological guidelines and tool support such as change-management systems, reusable libraries, translators, decision support tools, and support for validation and verification."
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Forschungsgebiete/viewForschungsgebietOWL/id39instance'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/WBS/dvr/owltools/merge/type'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#ResearchTopic'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id716instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#isAbout'	b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Forschungsgebiete/viewForschungsgebietOWL/id104instance'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1048instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In the IST project SEKT &#8211; Semantically Enabled Knowledge\r\nTechnologies &#8211; one of the case studies [BCC+05] aims at providing\r\nan intelligent Frequently Asked Questions system, Iuriservice prototype\r\nII, that will offer help to newly appointed judges in Spain. This iFAQ\r\nuses ontology based Semantic Web technologies to retrieve FAQ to reply\r\nqueries posed in natural language. In order to construct the underlying\r\nontology, we used the ontology engineering methodology DILIGENT.\r\nDILIGENT [PTSS04] methodology is intended to support domain experts\r\nin a distributed setting to engineer and evolve ontologies with\r\nthe help of a fine-grained methodological approach based on Rhetorical\r\nStructure Theory [MT87]. Although, knowledge acquisition and other\r\ncontent issues are not discussed in this paper, harmonization efforts for\r\nknowledge modelling are required by discussing the ontology. During the\r\ndiscussion, participants exchange arguments which may support or object\r\nto certain ontology engineering decisions. As any legal professional\r\nknows, tracking the argumentation of decisions is essential in allowing\r\nlater readers to understand them.\r\nWe will present an evaluation framework to evaluate the methodology\r\nwithin this particular context. We will take a detailed look at the development\r\nof the ontology and especially the novel experience of using\r\na wiki to support the collaborative ontology engineering and to capture\r\nthe ongoing discussion of the ontology. First results of this evaluation\r\nwill be presented.'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Personen/viewPersonOWL/id1901instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#homepage'	b'None'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1265instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Technical scenarios in areas like automotive or production systems will increasingly consist of a large number of components cooperating in potentially unlimited and dynamically changing networks to satisfy the functional requirements of their execution environment. Due to the high complexity it will be impossible to explicitly design the behaviour of the components for every potentially arising situation. Therefore, it will be necessary to leave an adequate degree of freedom allowing for a self-organised behaviour. Organic Computing (OC) has developed the vision of selforganising systems adapting robustly to dynamically changing environments without running out of control. This paper focuses on the design of a generic system architecture which allows for self-organisation but at the same time enables adequate reactions to control the, sometimes completely unexpected, emerging global behaviour of these self-organised technical systems.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id970instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Mobile terminals, such as cellular phones and PDAs,\r\nhave an enormous advertising potential: they are extremely\r\npopular and most people carry such devices with them all\r\nday, enabling personalized advertising. However, there is\r\na serious danger that the Spam wave, known from e-mail\r\ncommunication, will spillover to mobile devices. In addition,\r\nit is important to take protection of private data seriously,\r\nbecause mobile terminals are also used for personal\r\ncommunication. In this article we discuss the special features\r\nand challenges of mobile advertising and introduce\r\nthe MoMa-system for mobile advertising. MoMa supports\r\npersonalized advertising using context information while\r\nguaranteeing data protection. We also name criteria for the\r\ncomparison of mobile advertising systems and apply them\r\nto compare MoMa to other approaches.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id83instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b"Distributed knowledge management systems (DKMS) have been\r\nsuggested to meet the requirements of today's knowledge\r\nmanagement. Peer-to-peer systems offer technical foundations for\r\nsuch distributed systems. To estimate the value of P2P-based\r\nknowledge management evaluation criteria that measure the\r\nperformance of such DKMS are required. We suggest a concise\r\nframework for evaluation of such systems within different usage\r\nscenarios. Our approach is based on standard measures from the\r\ninformation retrieval and the databases community. These measures\r\nserve as input to a general evaluation function which is used to\r\nmeasure the efficiency of P2P-based KM systems. We describe test\r\nscenarios as well as the simulation software and data sets\r\nthat can be used for that purpose."
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewExternerAutorOWL/id684instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#name'	b'Marta Poblet'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewExternerAutorOWL/id344instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#name'	b'David Aha'
b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id527instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'In this paper, we discuss Conceptual Knowledge Discovery in Databases (CKDD) in its connection with Data Analysis. Our approach is based on Formal Concept Analysis, a mathematical theory which has been developed and proven useful during the last 20 years. Formal Con\xc3\x82\xc2\xad cept Analysis has led to a theory of conceptual information systems which has been applied by using the management system TOSCANA in a wide range of domains. In this paper, we use such an application in database marketing to demonstrate how methods and procedures of CKDD can be applied in Data Analysis. In particular, we show the interplay and integration of data mining and data analysis techniques based on For\xc3\x82\xc2\xad mal Concept Analysis. The main concern of this paper is to explain how the transition from data to knowledge can be supported by a TOSCANA system. To clarify the transition steps we discuss their correspondence to the five levels of knowledge representation established by R. Brachman and to the steps of empirically grounded theory building proposed by A. Strauss and J. Corbin.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id754instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'Intelligent systems based on first-order logic on the one hand, and on artificial neural networks (also called connectionist systems) on the other, differ substantially.  It would be very desirable to combine the robust neural networking machinery with symbolic knowledge representation and reasoning paradigms like logic programming in such a way that the strengths of either paradigm will be retained. Current state-of-the-art research, however, fails by far to achieve this ultimate goal. As one of the main obstacles to be overcome we perceive the question how symbolic knowledge can be encoded by means of connectionist systems: Satisfactory answers to this will naturally lead the way to knowledge extraction algorithms and to integrated neural-symbolic systems.'

b'http://www.aifb.uni-karlsruhe.de/Publikationen/viewPublikationOWL/id1236instance'	b'http://swrc.ontoware.org/ontology#abstract'	b'To achieve better interoperability among intelligent applications, and to relieve knowledge engineers from the burden of developing ontologies from scratch, it is critical to reuse ontologies. However, there are two main reasons why the reuse of ontologies is rare: (1) current ontology repositories allow only simple keyword-based search facilities, and (2) even when a user finds an ontology, the information about the ontology quality and (re)usability is not available.\r\n\r\nIn this paper, we present an Open Rating System based approach for ontology evaluation. The core Open Rating System model is extended with topic-specific trust to provide more accurate personalized ontology rankings. Our model is partially implemented in Knowledge Zone - a webbased ontology repository where users can submit their ontologies, annotate them with metadata, search for existing ontologies, find out their rankings based on user reviews, post their own reviews, and rate reviews.'
